## Confirmed duplication

The crimes scan output matches what's in the files:

- **`src/sanitize-a.ts:10-36` `sanitizeUserInput`**, **`src/sanitize-b.ts:9-35` `sanitizeText`**, **`src/sanitize-c.ts:9-35` `cleanMessage`** — byte-identical apart from local-variable renaming (`working` / `cleaned` / `normalised`) and the exported function name. Same null guard, same `String().trim()`, same control-char strip, same 1000-char cap, same `<`/`>` and `\x` early-outs, same `[!?]{3,}` punctuation gate, same caps-ratio downcasing. There is no behavioural divergence to preserve.

## Refactor proposal

**Consolidated module:** `src/sanitize.ts`

```ts
export function sanitize(input: unknown): string {
  if (input === null || input === undefined) return "";
  let working = String(input).trim();
  working = working.replace(/[\x00-\x1f]/g, "");      // same intent as the existing [ -] strip
  working = working.replace(/\s+/g, " ");
  if (working.length > 1000) working = working.slice(0, 1000);
  if (working.length === 0) return "";
  if (working.startsWith("<") || working.startsWith(">")) return "";
  if (working.includes("\\x")) return "";
  if ((working.match(/[!?]{3,}/g) ?? []).length > 5) return "";
  const upperRatio =
    working.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, "").length /
    (working.replace(/\s/g, "").length || 1);
  if (upperRatio > 0.9 && working.length > 30) working = working.toLowerCase();
  return working;
}
```

Notes on the signature:
- `input: unknown` is honest — each variant accepts `null`/`undefined` at runtime despite the `(x: string)` type. Callers that pass strings still typecheck.
- One exported name, `sanitize`. The three existing names (`sanitizeUserInput`, `sanitizeText`, `cleanMessage`) are arbitrary aliases and should not survive as re-exports — that just re-creates the multiple-sources-of-truth problem the refactor exists to remove.

## Files that change

| File | Change |
|---|---|
| `src/sanitize.ts` | **new** — contains `sanitize` |
| `src/sanitize-a.ts` | **delete** (after migrating call sites of `sanitizeUserInput` → `sanitize`) |
| `src/sanitize-b.ts` | **delete** (after migrating `sanitizeText` → `sanitize`) |
| `src/sanitize-c.ts` | **delete** (after migrating `cleanMessage` → `sanitize`) |
| any call site importing the three old names | update import path + name |

The fixture has no external call sites of these three sanitizers, so deletion is safe here; in a real repo, do the rename pass first and remove the old files in the same commit so search-and-replace stays atomic.

## What the refactor deliberately does *not* consolidate

The scan also flagged two related items that look adjacent but should be handled separately, not folded into `sanitize`:

1. **`assertAdminA/B/C`** (the `duplicated_role_status_plan_check` finding) — these have *different* semantics: A is `role === "admin"`, B widens to `|| "owner"`, C is the negation `role !== "admin"`. Collapsing them into one helper would silently change behaviour. The right move is a `src/policy.ts`-style module exposing distinct predicates (`isAdmin`, `isAdminOrOwner`, `isNotAdmin`), then migrate each call site to the predicate it actually wants. Out of scope for the sanitiser consolidation.
2. **`recordSanitiseEvent`** in `telemetry-a.ts` / `telemetry-b.ts` (the `exact_duplicate_block` finding) — these are byte-identical and should collapse to a single `src/telemetry.ts`. That also resolves the two `Temporal Recklessness` findings against `Date.now()` to one location, where a `now: () => number` parameter can be injected.
